1.c: No improvements.
1.b: None.

areaDesc.5: Sparsely settled. Fair Grounds are located in southwest corner. Very heavy traffic on west border on U.S. Highway #41. A grade school is located in north central part of area. Known as "Nordheim". The toughest part of city with a mixed population. Spotted with some fine residences.

1.c: Along the west side is low land.
1.b: All modern utility improvements. Municipal Golf Park.

areaDesc.5: This area relied wholly upon the Paine Lumber Company operations and when the plant shut-down, there was no other source of income. The majority of these people were Russian immigrants- no work for them today. Roosevelt Grade School (one of the finest in the city) is located on Sawyer Avenue and 4th.

1.c: Soo Line Railroad runs east and north through area. The area to the east and north has several manufactoring plants.
1.b: All public utilities. Good bus transportation.

areaDesc.5: No schools in area, but to the west in C-1 there are a grade and junior high schools. Not much can be said of the area. Spotted.

1.c: None.
1.b: All improvements, good bus transportation.

areaDesc.5: Grade and junior high schools (Merrill School), St. Josephats Roman Catholic Church and school. In D-6 (north) there are 2 Lutheran churches. The northwest section has suffered due to the closing down of the Paine Lumber Company in 1933 (still closed), now understood to be negotiating for partial re-opening. Quite spotted- poor buildings and good ones adjacent.

1.c: None
1.b: All improvements, good transportation, close to main business district.

areaDesc.5: The oldest area in city and at one time had 31 saw-mills along Fox River and mill owners built their fine large homes along Algoma Blvd. There are 2 grade schools (Lincoln and Read), a State Teacher’s Training School, also Oshkosh High School southeast of D-4, and a number of churches of different denominations in or closely adjacent to the area. The only large apartment house in the city (The Indian Trail) of 30 units is located in D-4 to the south. Very spotted.

1.c: Adjacency to industry.
1.b: Has all utility improvements and east side of Algoma Street has many fine old homes, well kept, owned by former mill owners and their families.

areaDesc.5: On west side of Algoma Street there are also some exceptionally fine old frame homes of 6 to 10 rooms with well kept grounds. Close to several schools in C-2 to the east. On southeast corner of area on the corner of Jackson and Algoma Blvds. there is a new $1,000,000 County Court House under construction.

1.c: Cemetery to west, no improvements, several taverns on west.
1.b: None.

areaDesc.5: A continuation of Elmwood Avenue outside city- shows some better class homes from $4,000-$6,000. Due to shut-down of Paine Lumber Company, sash and door plant, on both sides of Fox River, this district has suffered very severely. Sparsely settled.

1.c: No sewerage- streets unimproved.
1.b: Adjacent to B-1 and Lake Winnebago.

areaDesc.5: Has a good future with any increase in population. Homes are small. Sparsely settled to north. Quite spotted.

1.c: No sewers, no transportation.
1.b: Lake Winnebago and park area to east. North part heavily wooded. Restricted.

areaDesc.5: If building ever resumes this area should have good activity. Park land has only been developed in past 5 years. Trend of growth will be in this vicinity. (* Lots only)

1.c: Bowen Street is known as County Trunk A and has very heavy continuous traffic.
1.b: Proximity to park and lake. Good transportation, all modern conveniences.

areaDesc.5: Low area south of B-1 to Lincoln Avenue extending 3 blocks to west, subject to floods in spring. Longfellow Grade School on Grove Street, and to the west in D-7 is located St. Mary's Catholic School (grade and high school). There is also an Evangelical church in this area. More building activity took place in this area in 1936 and 1937 than in any other part of the city. Very spotted.

1.c: Nothing.
1.b: Opposite Menominee Park. Longfellow grade school south and west within 3 blocks. Immediate neighborhood has good homes. All mdoern conveniences.

areaDesc.5: Mercy Hospital to the south. A very good grade of property due to adjacency to park to the east. Spotted.

1.c: None.
1.b: Good schools- all modern conveniences- good transportation.

areaDesc.5: Good grade school (Longfellow School) and Roman Catholic grade and high school (St. Mary's), 2 Evangelical churches, Lutheran Church, an St. Mary's Catholic Church, all within 4 or 5 blocks of district (in C-4) and part of area faces Menominee Park. A very desirable locality in which to live. Spotted with good and bad buildings.

1.c: Both Soo Line and Chicago and North Western Railroad run through area.
1.b: All public utilities. Close to business section.

areaDesc.5: Close to downtown business center. No schools in area itself. There are some colored people in business section between D-6 and D-7 and in the business district on Division north of Church to Irving Street.

1.c: Chicago and North Western Railroad runs through center. Industry to the south.
1.b: All public utilities. Close to business center.

areaDesc.5: Interspersed with industry. Good grade school in northwest corner on east Irving Street. Parochial school on corner of Bowen and Winnebago (in southern part). St. Mary's Catholic Church, grade and high schools on the corner of Monroe and Merritt. St. Mary's Hospital is across the street from the schools- on Boyd and Merritt. Spotted with some good homes.

1.c: None, except Rahr Brewery in D-8 from which smoke is sometimes objectionable.
1.b: All improvements, good transportation, close to lake.

areaDesc.5: Washington (grade) School is on Otter Street- west end of area. On Bowen Street west is a Lutheran Church and grade school. That part of area adjacent to lake has good possibilities in future. Quite spotted. Some new residential building along lake between Otter and Washington Streets.

1.c: None.
1.b: On lake. All utilities.

areaDesc.5: Occupied mainly by Rahr Brewing Company. If this should ever be dismantled, the character of area would change to a "B" rating.

1.c: None. A dry cleaning plant in north end.
1.b: All modern conveniences.

areaDesc.5: Although the lots are shallow that fact that they are right on the lake and river with fine beach makes them very desirable. Spotted homes, good and fair. Age of homes on east is approximately 40 years and on south 10 years. Washington Grade School within 5 blocks in C-5.

1.c: Soo Line Railroad on the east side.
1.b: All public utilities. Good transportation

areaDesc.5: Close to South Park Grade School in C7 on Florida and Delaware Streets. Spotted in south.

1.c: 2 stone quarries, one immediately west of C-7 and one located in D-11.
1.b: South Park in center. All modern conveniences, streets improved, good transportation.

areaDesc.5: Property east and south of park, which has 2 artificial lakes, is quite desirable. Due to the 2 adjacent quarries there is a detrimental influence for the best type of homes on property in this area. When blasts (which sometimes have a load of 1 1/2 tons of dynamite) in the quarry to the west go off, distinct tremors are felt as the area is on rock strata. South Park Grade School is on N. Delaware Street. Mostly settled by Germans. Very Spotted.

1.c: None, except aforementioned.
1.b: All improvements are in although most of the streets are unimproved.

areaDesc.5: Spotted and sparsely settled on south, also some vacant land. Mostly Germand population. Smiths Grade School is on Oregon and 18th. The east side is quite desirable due to proximity to lake.

1.c: None.
1.b: Transportation and all other improvements.

areaDesc.5: This area is in what is known as "South Side District" with a very large percentage of German families- good and dependable. St. Vincent's Catholic Church, also grade and high school are on South Park Avenue. St. John's Catholic Church and school also are on South Park Avenue- 2 blocks to the west. There is an Evangelical Church across from St. John's. This whole district is well supplied with grade schools. Close to main business district of south side. Very spotted.

1.c: Soo Line and Chicago, Milwaukee & St. Paul Railroad run through the area. Close to industry on east and north.
1.b: All modern improvements. Good transportation. Close to South Park on the south.

areaDesc.5: Stone quarries to southwest of area. Catholic church and grade school located on Knapp and 5th Streets. Franklin Grade School is on 6th and Dakota. On the easterly part, the area has 3 business districts (Ohio, Oregon, and S. Main Street), Oregon Street being the main street on the South Oshkosh side of the river.

1.c: Chicago and North Western Railroad on the east side. County Trunk "A" on east and Highway 41 on west.
1.b: Lake.

areaDesc.5: The easten half is swamp land and the western part is occupied by homes.

1.c: Quarry located on northwest corner of area, also 2 abandoned quarries in southern half.
1.b: None. (Limited public utilities.)

areaDesc.5: Sparsely settled. To the west of area is another abandoned stone quarry and to the west and southwest is farm land.
